There are four distinct types of attributes, those being nominal attributes, ordinal attributes, interval-scaled attributes and ratio-scaled attributes. Furthermore, there are also discrete and continuous classifications for distinguishing types of attributes. Since there are a total of 292 attributes in the primary dataset we will not describe the specific attribute type for each attribute. Instead, we will provide examples of attributes from the dataset that fulfill the criteria of the different attribute types.

Nominal Attributes

Nominal attributes are those which are qualitative and do not have any inherent order or ranking. An example of this type of attribute within the dataset is the sub_area attribute. This attribute represents the name of the district that the data sample (property) belongs to. It takes on values such as "Juzhnoe Butovo" and "Perovo".

Ordinal Attributes

Ordinal attributes are again qualitative. However, the values that these attributes take on have a meaningful order. In the primary housing market dataset there are no attributes that are ordinal.

Interval-Scaled Attributes

Interval-scaled attributes are ordered, and are those which, as the name implies, are measured on a particular equal-sized interval scale. The distinguishing factor between interval-scaled attributes and ratio-scaled attributes is that interval-scaled attributes do not have a true zero point (i.e. they can be positive, zero, or negative). After observing the name and meaning of each of the attributes in the primary dataset, we did not find any attributes that appeared interval-scaled. We further check this observation below:

In [10]:
# Check for negative values in DataFrame
for col_name in list(df.columns):
    col = df[col_name]
    
    if col.dtype == "float64" or col.dtype == "int64":
        neg_values = []
        
        for val in col:
            if not math.isnan(val) and val < 0:
                neg_values.append(val)
                
        if neg_values:
            print("Column: {}".format(col_name))
            print("Negative values: {}".format(len(neg_values)))

Ratio-Scaled Attributes

Ratio-scaled attributes, like those which are interval-scaled, are ordered measurements which have a particular scale. However, what differentiates ratio-scaled attributes is that they have a true zero point (i.e. they can be positive or zero). An example of a ratio-scaled attribute within the housing market dataset is full_sq. This attribute represents the total area of the property in square meters. Since area has an inherent zero-point, as you cannot have a house with negative area, this is a clear example of a ratio-scaled attribute.

Discrete Attributes

Discrete attributes are attributes which take on a finite or countably infinite set of possible values. The attribute product_type is an example of a discrete attribute within the primary dataset. This attribute states whether the property was bought as an investment property, or for owner-occupancy. Since there are two possible values this attribute can take on (i.e. "OwnerOccupier" or "Investment"), it has a finite set of values and is therefore a discrete attribute.

Continuous Attributes

Continuous attributes, in contrast to discrete attributes, take on real valued numbers over a continuous range. An example of this type of attribute in the Russian housing market dataset is metro_min_walk, which provides the time it would take to walk to the metro on foot from the property (in minutes). This attribute has floating-point values over a continuous range and can therefore be classified as a continuous attribute.

1.3. Feature Selection¶

The primary Russian housing market dataset contains a significant number of attributes, 292 in total. Consequently, for this investigation we will perform feature selection to select a few attributes which seem interesting and/or significant for predicting property sale price to study in data exploration and visualisation. Firstly, we will perform manual feature selection by examining the features and using domain knowledge to determine which attributes should not be investigated. We will then use metrics and data analysis techniques to determine which attributes seem most promising to examine.

Manual Selection¶

The following attributes were selected for data exploration and visualisation based upon our domain knowledge of what attributes would be significant in predicting house price and what attributes would be interesting to study.

price_doc - this attribute represents the sale price of the property. This attribute will be interesting to explore as it allows us to find trends in the price and determine what other attributes are correlated to house price. Furthermore, the sale price will be the target variable for our regression and forecasting methods.

full_sq - this attribute represents the total area of the property in square meters (including loggias, balconies and other non-residential living areas). We believe that the total area of the property would be a strong indicator for gauging the price of the property. As larger homes are generally more expensive than smaller ones.

sub_area - this attribute represents the name of the district that the property is within. Characteristics of the district, such as its reputation, its population, or whether it has a large central business district will all affect the price of the property and other property/neighbourhood attribute values. Because of this, we thought that it would be interesting to explore.

num_room - this attribute represents the number of living rooms in the property. Since the number of rooms is generally thought to be an indicator of house price (i.e. the more rooms the greater the price) we thought that investigating this attribute would be worthwhile.

build_year - this attribute represents the year that the property was built. Since newer appartments and homes are generally more expensive, we assume that this attribute will be useful for predicting house price. Furthermore, it may also allude to interesting relationships between house age and the district, or house age and the demographic information of the neighbourhood.

state - this attribute represents the condition that the property is in at the time of purchase. Properties in bad condition are typically purchased at a lower price since the home buyer will need to invest additional money into the property in order to fix it up. This attribute could therefore provide insight into predicting property price, as well as the general characteristics of people and/or properties within a particular district.

Below lists the 26 of the attributes with the highest absolute correlation to the house price. Due to the categorical data of this set not being encoded and ordinal this algorithm has only correlated numerical attributes. Attributes such as the number of rooms and size of the properties are shown to have a high positive correlation with price. While this is quite obvious, the algorithm also described some interesting relationships through the negative correlations. As the distance to the city center decreases, and the distance to features of the city centre such as garden rings, train stations and boulevards decrease, the price of houses increase.

Metric-Based Selection - Extreme Gradient Boosting¶

Another algorithm which determines stronger relationships between attributes and a target result such as the house price is Extreme Gradient Boosting. This algorithm constructs a gradient boosted tree, which is essentially an optimised decision tree, to assign attributes scores on how influential they are in classifying the output.

The algorithm requires categorical data to be encoded so the code below first converts all data of type object to an encoded label.

Parameters that the tree model for the XBG library require include the max depth of the tree, learning rate(eta) and error function.

In [14]:
for f in df_train.columns:
    if df_train[f].dtype=='object':
        lbl = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
        lbl.fit(list(df_train[f].values)) 
        df_train[f] = lbl.transform(list(df_train[f].values))

y_train = df_train.price_doc.values
x_train = df_train.drop(["id", "timestamp", "price_doc"], axis=1)


param = {'max_depth': 10, 'eta': 1, 'objective': 'reg:squarederror'}


dtrain = xgb.DMatrix(x_train, y_train, feature_names=x_train.columns.values)
model = xgb.train(dict(param, silent=0), dtrain, num_boost_round=10)

importance = model.get_score()
importance = dict(sorted(importance.items(), key=lambda importance: importance[1], reverse=True))
importance = dict(itertools.islice(importance.items(), 20))
importance

1.4. Statistical Information¶

Within this section we examine the statistical information of the selected attributes. This exploration provides a statistical overview of the attributes which will be useful for proposing pre-processing questions and in gaining a better understanding of the data. There are two categories of measures that provide us with a rather comprehensive picture of the data. These are measures of central tendency and measures of spread. We explore each category below.

Measures of Central Tendency¶

Measures of central tendency provide us with information about the "typical values" of a certain data distribution. With this information we can gather an understanding of what the values of a particular attribute are likely to be. Here we will examine four measures of central tendency: mean, median, midrange and mode. The mean tells us what the average value of the attribute is, the median tells us the midpoint of the values of the attribute (i.e. the point splitting the data into lower and higher halves), the midrange tells us the centre value of the range, and the mode tells us what value occurs the most.

2. Data Pre-Processing¶

2.1. Data Quality¶

Raw data generally isn't initially suitable for data mining. Poor data quality can dramatically reduce accuracy and lead to incorrect conclusions. Data quality may be affected by the introduction of noise from incorrect data entry or erroneous data from sensors. Outliers skew the distribution of attributes and missing values make it more difficult do get an accuracte representation of the model behind the data. The easiest method for dealing with outliers and missing values is to simply delete/drop them from the dataframe. This provides convenience at the expense of statistical significance due to smaller sample sizes. Therefore, where values are predictable/computatble, we apply methods which replace these values.

Data Mechanism¶

In our data pre-processing we make the assumption that the data is 'Missing at Random', such that missing values are independent of other attributes.

2.2. Data Cleaning¶

The process of data cleaning involves finding data with incorrect formatting, data with missing values, outliers, data that is erroneous, inconsistent, intentionally incorrect, irrelevant and malicious, and either correcting or removing those samples. The types of data mentioned here are collectively known as "dirty" data. We will briefly describe the types of dirty data below.

  • Outliers: data that is deviated from or inconsistent with other data in the dataset, also referred to as noise or anomolies
  • Formatting: data containing the same information with inconsistent formatting
  • Erroneous data: data that is erroneous with respect to other samples or in regard to the context of the information
  • Irrelevant data: data that does not affect the results of statistical or analitical methods
  • Inconsistent data: data that can be represented in two or more ways
  • Malicious data: data designed to cause damage or an undesired effect
  • Intentionally incorrect data: data that is intentionally entered to be incorrect
  • Incomplete (missing) data: data samples with missing variable information

For the process of data cleaning, all removals and corrections of data will be made to the complete dataframe df (the dataframe containing all attributes and all data samples (from both the test and train set)). These changes can then simply be applied to the selected attributes for data visualisation.

Outlier Detection¶

Here we apply a basic statistical method to check for outliers in the selected numerical attributes. This method simply checks if a value is plus or minus three standard deviations away from the mean of the attribute, and if so, classifies it as an outlier.

In [44]:
# Here we display the median of the selected attributes which contain numerical data
print("{:<30} {}".format("Numerical Attribute", "No. Outliers"))
print("{:<30} {}".format("-------------------", "------------"))
for num_col in list(df_exp.describe().columns):
    stddev = df[num_col].std()
    mean = df[num_col].mean()
    lower_bound = mean - 3 * stddev
    upper_bound = mean + 3 * stddev
    num_outliers = len(df[ (df[num_col] < lower_bound) | (df[num_col] > upper_bound) ][num_col])
    print("{:<30} {:.3f}".format(num_col, num_outliers))

Numerical Attribute            No. Outliers
-------------------            ------------
price_doc                      450.000

2.3. Data Transformation and Data Discretization¶

We cannot use numerical data for association rule mining since the total number of possible itemsets would increase significantly if we were to use them. One way to work around this is to perform attribute/feature construction and construct categorical attributes from the numerical ones. This is somewhat like binning, where we will define a fixed set of ranges for the categorical classes and simply assign a categorical class to the data sample based upon which range its numerical value falls into. In this initial data investigation, we will use this data transformation method on distance attributes in the dataset (e.g. park_km). However, in the final investigation when we are implementing the algorithms, we will most probably apply this technique to many numerical attributes in the Russian housing market dataset.

Distance to Park (park_km)

In [45]:

max         47.351538
Name: park_km, dtype: float64

Here we will define three distance classes for the park_km attribute, NEAR, MODERATE and FAR. The ranges that these classes represent were chosen by ourselves, using domain knowledge about what would be considered nearby, a moderate distance away, or far away. These ranges are [0.0, 1.0), [1.0, 2.0) and [2.0, 50.0), respectively (where 50.0 is set as the upper bound of the FAR range since the maximum value for this attribute is 47.35). Below we construct a new attribute from these classes.

In [46]:
# Add a 'park_km_class' column to the DataFrame filled with None values
df = df.assign(park_km_class=pd.Series([None for i in range(df.shape[0])]).values)
In [47]:
# Define a function for mapping from 'park_km' to 'park_km_class'
def park_km_class_mapping_func(x):
    if 0.0 <= x["park_km"] < 1.0:
        return "NEAR"
    elif 1.0 <= x["park_km"] < 2.0:
        return "MODERATE"
    elif 2.0 <= x["park_km"] < 50.0:
        return "FAR"
    else:
        print("Unexpected value: {}".format(x["park_km"]))
        return None
In [48]:
# Apply the mapping function to set the class values for 'park_km_class'
df["park_km_class"] = df.apply(park_km_class_mapping_func, axis=1)
In [49]:

MODERATE    10919
NEAR         9840
Name: park_km_class, dtype: int64

Above we see that the park_km_class attribute was successfully constructed from the park_km attribute. This can now be used to more efficiently represent the distance to the nearest park for a particular property in tasks such as association rule mining.

Here we will define three size classes (SMALL, MEDIUM, and LARGE) for the attribute full_sq. This attribute represents the total area of the property, and therefore the classes will simply define the size of the property categorically. Because these properties are in Russia, using our domain knowledge would not be as representative since we are not familiar with the apartment/home sizes within the country. As a result, we will base our class ranges off the statistics of the full_sq attribute displayed above. We believe that the quartiles are rather informative in regard to what different house sizes are common. Based on this information, the decided upon ranges for the three classes were [0.0, 45.0), [45.0, 65.0) and [65.0, 5500.0), respectively (again, the upper bound of the LARGE class was chosen based upon the maximum value for this attribute). This suggests that there may be a few large properties that have recently been sold on the market (perhaps mansions or castles). However, the fact that the majority of the data seems to fall within a relatively small range suggests that there are commonalities between properties beind sold. This may be a useful property to investigate for sale price prediction, and may aid our investigation of patterns with clustering and association rule mining.

3.2. Housing Market Share¶

Here we examine the housing market share of different attribute properties. Since we are interested in visualising what percentage of the dataset a particular value represents, we will use a pie chart for visualisation. We decided to explore three attributes from the dataset, product_type, ecology, and nuclear_reactor_raion. These are discussed in more detail below.

Property Product Type (product_type)¶

The product_type attribute specifies whether the property was purchased for owner occupancy, or as an investment property. We found that two thirds of the purchased properties were purchased as investment properties, while the remaining one third were purchased for the home buyer. This is a facinating observation. Later within this data investigation we find that the majority of the districts are within Moscow. This tells us that the real estate market within the past few years within Moscow has involved lots of investors buying properties in the area. This supports the notion that the vast majority of properties within this dataset are apartments, rather than houses. Since apartments are good for investment properties. Furthermore, if investors are purchasing properties, it generally means that the housing market is increasing in cost. This information may prove useful in our forecasting and regression investigations.

Property Ecological Zone Classification (ecology)¶

The attribute ecology represents the classification of the ecological zone where the house is located. This attribute takes on five possible values: no data, poor, satisfactory, good and excellent. Surprisingly, the most common ecological zone classification was poor, followed by good, excellent and then satisfactory (excluding no data). Since the majority of the districts are within Moscow, we assume that the poor ecological zones would be in built-up areas right in the middle of the city, with lots of buildings and few plants. In contrast, we assume that the good and excellent ecological zones are on the outskirts of Moscow, or even further out in more rural areas. Since each ecological zone classification has a significant number of properties, it will be interesting to observe relationships and correlations with this attribute in clustering and association rule mining.

Property Districts with Nuclear Reactors (nuclear_reactor_raion)¶

The attribute nuclear_reactor_raion specifies the presence of existing nuclear reactors within the district that the property is located in. We thought that this attribute would be interesting to explore since we assumed that the value of a property would be significantly less if it were within an area in which a nuclear reactor was present. Moreover, we wanted to see what percentage of properties belonged to a district in which a nuclear reactor was located. We found (through observing the pie chart below) that only 3% of the properties in the dataset were located in a district where a nuclear reactor was present. We hypothesise that this means that the nuclear reactors around Moscow are located within a particular few districts. It will be interesting to observe whether this district with a nuclear reactor has any strong relationships with other attributes in the database when we do clustering and association rule mining. Furthermore, it may be a strong attribute for the task of classifying properties into different districts (at least for a few of the districts within the database).

3.4. District Property Prices¶

Here we investigate the prices of properties within each district. By sorting the districts by average sale price, we find that the district with the most expensive average sale price is Hamovniki, and the district with the least expensive average sale price is Poselenie Klenovskoe. Interestingly, the most expensive property in the dataset is not within Hamovniki. Moreover, the districts with the most expensive average property price do not have a wider distribution that is evenly spread out. Instead, like the other districts, they have a group of property prices which appear to be around the average price, and then some expensive properties that seems relatively spaced out. The district Arbat is unique in this regard, where it appears to only have a few properties in total. From this information, we gather that using sale price for classifying properties into districts may be quite useful.

3.5. Price by Property Distance to Utilities¶

Below we examine how distances to local public services effect the sale price of properties. The most apparent relationship is that properties close to local public services are, as a whole, more expensive than properties that are located further away from these services. We see this through the right-skewed nature of the data distributions. However, being the "closest" does not seem to mean that the property will be one of the most expensive. The most expensive properties appear to be within a range that would be considered "close" to these services in comparison to all of the other properties. We observe that the distance to particular services that is considered "close" changes between services. For example, the most expensive properties are all within 5km from the nearest market shop (market_shop_km). Whereas the most expensive properties are all within just 0.75km from the nearest green zone (green_zone_km). This insight informs us that for data transformations, like those within 2.3. Data Transformation and Data Discretization, we will need to consider the differences in what is considered "close". Based upon the data distributions below, this information is assume to assist greatly in predicting sale price. As algorithms such as the multilayer perceptron should be able to learn for example that if a property is 40km away from the nearest school, then it's price should be no greater than 20,000,000 rubles.

    ax.scatter(x=df[d], y=(df["price_doc"]))

3.6. House Material¶

Here we investigate the different materials that properties in the dataset are built out of. Our first investigation looks at the overall material distribution in the dataset. We see that panel is the most common material that purchased properties are made of by a significant margin. Wood on the other hand appears to be the main material of a minimal number of properties, while the rest of the other materials seem to have relatively the same counts. We then examine the distribution of materials per district (i.e. sub_area) and interestingly find that different districts rather distinctively use different materials. Within the districts examined, we see that panel, brick and wood in some cases represent the material of the majority of properties sold within that district. This attribute may therefore be useful in the task of district classification. Lastly, we explore the relationship between sale price and material. The most expensive sold properties are shown to be made out of brick. All materials appear to take part in the average property price, with the least spread distribution belonging to wood. There appears to be some limits in price of particular materials, which suggests to us that this attribute may also be useful for regression analysis in predicting sale price.

3.7. Prices of Different Property States¶

The following analysis examine the state attribute, which represents the condition of the property (1 meaning the property is in a poor condition, and 4 meaning the property is in an immaculate condition). Intuitively, we thought that the poorer the condition of the property, the less it's sale price. However, we see that this is not necessarily the case. The below violin plot shows that between condition classes 1-3, the sale price distributions are relatively the same. The peaks of each plot show a slight increase as condition improves, although there is no significant differences. In contrast, the 4th class, which means the property is in great condition, does seem to slightly increase the general property sale price (as the distribution is much more spread out). From this analysis, we conclude that the state attribute may not be as significant of an indicator for sale price as we previously expected.

3.8. Time Series Visualisation¶

Here we analyse the general time series characteristics of the data. Specifically, we look at the monthly average house sale price over time. Firstly, we are able to see that, after pre-processing, the dataset contains property sales from August 2011 to June 2015. In the first half of 2012 there was a rather large increase in property price, before it slowly dropped back down in the second half of the year. Since the beginning of 2013 however, property sale price has rather steadily increased. The fact that there is a trend present in the data may make forecasting methods quite accurate at predicting house price. Furthermore, investigating the performance of regression methods with and without time information may lead to interesting results we can examine in the final report.

3.9. Influence of Size on House Price¶

From plotting both full_sq and life_sq against price we can see how they each influence price and the overall difference between them. From the plot, we can see a gradual positive gradient of life_sq and full_sq as the price increases, allowing us to explicitly the see the strong positive correlation between price that we saw in our correlation matrix. Apart from the majority of points, we saw a few outliers where full_sq and or life_sq were far greater yet price was still at the low end of the distribution. It seems likely that some of these points are noise, but we have no other mechanism for determining their validity. As per our data cleaning section, the exception is when life_sq is greater than full_sq.

By taking the difference of life_sq and full_sq we extract the impact of non-residential areas on price. From this we see a far lower degree of influence over house prices as points stay relatively low and flat as price increases.

3.10. Insights into Housing Construction over Time¶

Here we look at how price changes depending on the age of the building. We see that as we draw nearer to the current year that price stabilizes, which would merely be the result of the increasing amount of data points. Yet, without taking into account the sparsity and volatility of earlier build years we can still see a general trend of decline from 1950. Looking at the data, after 1950, prices have steadily been declining after a large drop in 1950 followed by a steady increase until just after 2000. These drop offs could be associated with firstly, the building boom that occurred post-war around 1954 by the soviet union and secondly the 2008 financial crisis or Russian great recession. Prior to 1950, the majority of housing would've been made up of houses rather than large apartment complexes, hence sporadic nature of price in years prior.
